% ---------- ABSTRACT ----------
\pagenumbering{roman}
\begin{abstract}
In this study, It checks how can basic rule-based ai can predict the Seattle Weather, finding out if it has either rainy days or dry days, and also another ai if it can check if it has warm or chilly. This shows straight forward basic ai, with no need of complex training alike with machine learning, but this ai still can give useful results most of the time. With the data values pulled from the CSV, the research built 2 different rule-based ai models to test and compare them. One model assumes the day is wet if the drops hits more than 0.1 mm, and the other model says it's warm if its temperature hits more that 10 Celsius.

Models were run on Python using libraries such as Pandas, Numpy, Matplotlib, and ScikitLearn. The performance gets checked through the measure metrics via accuracy, precision, recall and F1 score. The first model finding says that it hit 96.4\% accuracy and 100\% at precision but the recall at 92.6\%. With the second model it received all perfect scores on every metric score, perfectly sorting all the warm from cold days with no errors

This shows the rule-based is not very flexible but can work well when you need clear fast results. Still even though these model don't learn over time. They're very dependable when the data is steady. So when the weather suddenly shifts or any info and data is missing, the performance of the model will drop quickly. So with that, their open structures makes the decision easier to understand, which can help in important situations. Adding them on with learning algorithms can boost how they can quickly react to real-time world conditions. In essence, this rule-based model can give solid useful weather prediction.

\end{abstract}
