% ---------- INTRODUCTION ----------
\pagenumbering{arabic}
\section{Introduction}


Weather predictions plays a key role in today’s world. From how we travel around, cultivating plants, gatherings, staying safe and how we simply go normal in our daily lives. Good predictions empower people and groups to decide wisely, lessen dangers, and gear up for whatever comes. Though today’s methods frequently utilize sophisticated computer programs, space-based observations, alongside detailed simulations of the atmosphere, even basic techniques can reveal useful information. Essentially, some AI works by following a set of clear instructions; if this happens, then do that. Because they are so straightforward to understand and also easy to build, these systems come in handy where processing power isn’t abundant, or knowing how a decision was reached matters.

We made two rule-based artificial intelligence models that predict Seattle weather, if a day is rainy or not. These systems rely on established rules. One looks at how much it rains or snows, or drizzles and to decide if a day qualifies as "wet." Testing both with past weather records. Then figures out if the day was warm or cold by looking at the highest temperature, then finally, we check it by how the prediction matched up with the real weather data from the dataset.

Both of the models are scored using key measurements such as accuracy, precision. Recall and finally the F1 score. Instead of merely just noting the correct responses, these numbers demonstrate the actual effectiveness each one are. Accuracy gives a general sense of how correct it is, precision shows how trustworthy the positive results are, recall shows the success at the findings it matters, and finally the F1 score is the middle ground between both precision and recall.

This finds at what will work and what does not work. With AI that follows fixed-based rules. Even though the system is not always accurate at predicting the outcome as more the recent models, the simplicity, usability and how can easily people can understand them, which make them useful where speed is important and needed in crucial events.





% ---------- LITERATURE REVIEW ----------
\section{Literature Review}


\subsection{What is Rule-based?}

According to GeeksforGeeks (2024), These systems make decisions, carry out tasks, or draw conclusions using a set of predetermined rules and logic.Essentially, these systems operate methodically. First, they hold a collection of "when this happens, do that" of rules. Next, where the component examines the new information, comparing it to those rules. In the end, when a match is found, the model will then perform the chosen action orwill reach a decision.  Since every choice directly link to a clear rule, and this system gives out trustworthy transparent results, making it easier to understand the logic behind it and to confirm how it operates. Therefore, they excel when dealing within situations where it is stable, like doing regular inspections, meeting regulation and rules, or handling customer service concerns. While these systems are consistent, however they can not be improved with time because as they have trouble dealing with unanticipated events. In result, if in a scenario where it deviates away from their predetermined instruction, system errors or someone needs to manually fix it. Rule-Based systems has been the starting point for artificial intelligence as because they are always reliable and straightforward. But since they dont learn anything or can't adjust to some approaches, they very lack flexibility. 
\subsection{Relative Review in Rule-Based AI in Weather Prediction}
Smart tool like analyzing the weather data are becoming more traction since more of the farmers are looking ways to grow plants effectively while adapting to the changes of climates. With more recent techniques such like machine learning, are getting more traction to its adaptable and flexible system, while traditional ai system like rule-based are based on well- established pre-written rules, are still important like machine learning as they can still predict weather pattern and planning crops planting. Due to the fact that this system uses logic created by experts, they can convert variables like heat, moisture, and even precipitation into useful practical guidance for how to protect harvest, when to water, and to estimate how much it expects to produce. Egypt serves as a good example of why is the approach is so effective, given how much the agriculture rely so much depends if there is consistent weather, changes in the temperature and rain have a huge impact on crop yields and the quality of the farm ground.  A research study from (Mohamed et al., 2025), says that a straightforward guidance rooted in current forecasts can helps smaller farms thrive; where these tools are valuable when folks need to grasp why a suggestion is being made, fostering trust since everything is out in the open. Because rule-based system struggle so much with the rapid of changing weather patterns since they sometimes fail to conform its expectations. Thereby, even though these system can help farm into adapting to different conditions, they can perform better when combined with like learning techniques like machine learning where it can be used in like image recognition as the predict weather changes more easier and quicker. This combination boosts reliability, precision, and moreover extends reach.



% ---------- METHODS ----------
\section{Methods}
In this research paper, we checked how two rule based AI models which i created to  forecasted weather by using Seattle’s historical climate patterns. Info taken from a CSV included details like weather condition, wind movement, or peak temperature values. We used Pandas for cleaning up data, while NumPy tackled math operations; Matplotlib drew charts and plots, whereas Scikit-learn tracked outcomes such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 scores.

The first AI model sorted days into "wet" or `"dry" using recorded weather and a 0.1 mm rainfall precipitation threshold. We added \texttt{"actual\_wet"} to mark the true wet days, alongside \texttt{"predicted\_wet"} for predictions from our model. The second AI model checks whether a day was "warm" based on the maximum temperature, considering it warm if it is at or above 10 degrees Celsius. We used the same steps to find \texttt{"actual\_warm"} and \texttt{"predicted\_warm"}.

measured each model’s performance, then displayed outcomes plainly through bar charts that lined up values next to one another so easily spotting gaps in accuracy, precision, recall, or F1 score became straightforward.

However, this project still had some limitations as the model result depended so much on how well the data was, so small errors or mistake in the gap might lead to serious issues. Adding on, AI like rule-based might frequently find itself to have some difficulty to adapt and perform badly in unexpected situation because it ignores and overlooks small changes in the patterns it gets. In the end, changes in the weather may give incorrectly in the data sets the dont change at all.



