% ---------- DISCUSSION ----------
\section{Discussion}
In the results it showed that both rule based model were effective when predicting Seattle weather. However the first model where it label days either it is dry or wet, did around 96.4\% in accuracy, and a perfect 100\% with precision, but recall got around 92.6\%, and with F1 score with a 92.6\%. Which means the false alarm were uncommon since it rarely call dry days by wet when actually they were not. Still it still marked some days as dry instead of wet. Cause of this some of the wet days were still categorized as dry day since the result of this gap. Where farming, traveling, and doing outdoor activities relies heavily when you know when it will rain, missing those predictions could lead to a big trouble

On the other hand with the model two nails without failure on both warm and cold days. This  model passed all test with perfect recall,spot on accuracy, and 100\% precision and a max score on the F1 Score metrics. where as not a single point of data was missed and everything perfectly lined up, because of the consistent temperature it steady cutoff that caught warm gaps. Thanks to its dependability, this actually makes it easier for like industries like farming, use of power, and travel may actually apply this method when planning with weather related.

Despite with all of the positive results, there are still few drawbacks that is needs to be noted. Cause the quality and accuracy of the data hinges on how well will the model can perform. While it is unclear if the performance numbers seems to holding up on a changing environment, as when they can appear good results in previous situations. Since rule-based model gets tends to harshly criticized for being over rigid and unflexibe and have trouble when dealing with all strange weather conditions. Where fixed information are becoming less trustworthy overtime since the dataset isnt updated in real time, where the real actual weather change over time.

Even so, we encountered some few surprises, especially with how the first model performed. Even though the numbers of the precision looks to be good, it some wet prediction may have been missed due to the low recall. This gaps shows that even there is some possibility that a item could’ve labeled falsely, which can lead us might very much unprepared if when it rains.

While for everyday use, these model would perform far better if they were using like machine learning, since theyre better for daily use when it comes for basic weather prediction. Where advanced versions could incorporate extra variable and dynamically adjusting for their interactions instead where of depending alone on the basic data. Which can potentially lead to more accurate forecast in real time scenarios.

It also revealed in the results the how important it is on to modify the data, especially when adding new updates to improve on the accuracy of the forecast. The models can respond quickly and more easily to unexpected weather condition if a wide broad of pool of data is gathered across longer period of time with such factors like wind speed, moisture levels, or changes in pressure.


In general, while our rule-based ai did performed okay at telling which between the two wet days and dry days or cold days and warm days, but it still faced some problems due to the inconsistent data, and rigid setups or the model within it.



% ---------- CONCLUSION ----------
\section{Conclusion}
To sum up, testing both rule-based systems on Seattle’s weather highlights what each can do well - and where they fall short. The first model splits rainy from dry days pretty accurately, hitting 96.4\% precision, yet its recall dipped to 92.6\%, meaning some damp days slipped through labeled as dry. Outside lab settings, that gap matters - spotting dry stretches helps, though catching every rainy day counts just as much, particularly in areas such as farming or travel planning where errors lead to actual setbacks. Meanwhile, the second system nailed every test run when sorting chilly from mild temperatures, proving solid for jobs tied to shifts in heat. Given how perfectly it did, alot of industries that rely on how accurate the temperature predict, such as where those sizing energy needs or when you need to schedule outdoor events, are not taking notice. However, with minimal change inside the date, while it make more sense to hold it off before adding it out in the real-world. 

Though results go beyond how well the method works, they point to deeper problems - especially when data’s shaky or software updates feel clunky in weather predictions. As conditions shift fast, rigid setups often stumble because weather won’t stick to a fixed script. These methods may seem fine at first, yet slowly reveal why adaptability matters more as time goes on. Coming projects need smart systems that respond live to quick changes - say, spikes in moisture, gusts of wind, or wild pressure drops - to make forecasts sharper.

These models show small tweaks matter - they keep existing info but learn patterns quicker. Because of this, fixing mistakes might boost forecast accuracy, helping sectors adapt faster as conditions shift. Even so, early results suggest setups reacting sooner and acting more like actual events.





